{"id":14881694,"mediaExerciseId":"9af9d0d2-1b4d-4de5-ab51-7fbf86b428cd","exerciseName":"2","chapterName":"19A","chapterTitle":"Determining the Target Cash Balance","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":671,"solutions":[{"id":6024096,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we need to calculate the target cash balance using the BAT model. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":60,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/15/6a31d886ac803002239e8a2668a48ce3/80c08cc9b3b53f30b8ae7e52a6d3a0c8/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":31,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/15/6a31d886ac803002239e8a2668a48ce3/80c08cc9b3b53f30b8ae7e52a6d3a0c8/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The annual interest rate is $4.5\\%$, fixed order cost is $F=\\$25$, and total cash needed is $T=\\$10,200$. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/15/6a31d886ac803002239e8a2668a48ce3/5e874747fefc34a4c6ede8634777633a/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/15/6a31d886ac803002239e8a2668a48ce3/5e874747fefc34a4c6ede8634777633a/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Using the BAT model, the target cash balance can be calculated as follows\n$$\\begin{align*}\nC&=\\sqrt{\\frac{2\\cdot T\\cdot F}{R}}\\\\\n&=\\sqrt{\\frac{2\\cdot\\$10,200\\cdot \\$25}{0.045}}\\\\\n&=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\$510,000}{0.045}}\\\\\n&=\\$3,366.5\n\\end{align*}$$\n\nThe trade-off between the opportunity costs of holding too much cash and the costs of holding too little cash is $\\$3,366.5$. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex"